            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371571419,
            "creation_date": 1371571419,
            "body": "<p>The following should work<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\\b(\\?{2})*:\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 17173707,
            "question_id": 17095504
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a1b1af8a33566e40eaa4f12890e7b653?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 133792,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 335439,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/335439/mrcaramori",
                "reputation": 2503,
                "display_name": "mrcaramori",
                "accept_rate": 62
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371153739,
            "creation_date": 1371152265,
            "body": "<p>Your regex means:<\/p>\n\n<p>Zero or more '??'<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>(\\\\?\\\\?)*\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Followed by not '?'<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>[^\\\\?]\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Ending in ':'<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>\\\\:\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So, your last match is the last colon. That's why the result offset is 6.<\/p>\n\n<p>You could change for:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>final Matcher m = Pattern.compile(\"((\\\\?){2})+\").matcher(\"a??:b:????:c\");\nwhile (m.find()){\n    //outputs 1 and 6, places \n    //you would have to start\n    //scaping...\n    System.out.println(m.start()); \n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 17095593,
            "question_id": 17095504,
            "last_edit_date": 1371153739
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/P6XgG.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1968644,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1768232,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1768232/durron597",
                "reputation": 32453,
                "display_name": "durron597",
                "accept_rate": 81
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1371153140,
            "creation_date": 1371152496,
            "body": "<p>The <code>*<\/code> means there can be zero of that group. So that capturing group can be the empty string. <code>[^\\\\?]<\/code> can be any character that isn't a <code>?<\/code>, as <code>?<\/code> is not a special character inside a character class. The <code>\\<\/code> is ignored.<\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore, <code>b:<\/code> (with an empty string preceding it) matches, and the second colon is your last (and, in this case, first) match.<\/p>\n\n<p>I think you simply want <code>\"(\\\\?\\\\?)*\\\\?:\"<\/code>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17095649,
            "question_id": 17095504,
            "last_edit_date": 1371153140
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4355355595eef30b4c7284927560c7ee?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 122134,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 315734,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/315734/mentics",
                "reputation": 7079,
                "display_name": "mentics",
                "accept_rate": 88
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1371494075,
            "creation_date": 1371494075,
            "body": "<p>It appears that just be reversing the regex it works. Putting the \"don't match a ?\" first, and then the \"any even number of ?'s\" seems to do the trick:<\/p>\n\n<p><code>[^?](\\\\?\\\\?)*:<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 17154387,
            "question_id": 17095504
        }
